{"type":"message","id":"4d3495a1","parentId":"45d2b86d","timestamp":"2026-03-29T14:44:50.471Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] Sim — **isso é do sistema de watchdog que estávamos a montar**, não da tua tarefa nova do frontend no PC.\n\n## O que aconteceu\nFicou uma **tarefa velha presa no registry**:\n\n- **nome:** Claude Code sidecar viability research (retest)\n- **modelo:** `anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5`\n- **iniciada:** 28/03 às 16:08\n- **estado no registry:** ainda como `running`\n\nSó que essa tarefa **já terminou há muito tempo**.  \nEntão o watchdog começou a te mandar updates falsos de uma tarefa fantasma.\n\n---\n\n## E a mensagem:\n> “Let me fix the PowerShell syntax:”\n\nisso também **não é a tua tarefa actual do frontend**.  \nIsso parece ser ruído/resíduo de um dos jobs/flows antigos que ficou mal encerrado.\n\n---\n\n## Resposta directa à tua pergunta\n**Não — isso não é a tarefa que deixaste rodando agora no PC.**  \nÉ lixo operacional do watchdog/registry antigo.\n\n---\n\n## Diagnóstico\nO bug aqui é claro:\n\n### o registry ficou com tarefa zombie\nOu seja:\n- a tarefa terminou\n- mas nunca foi marcada como concluída/removida\n- o watchdog continuou a tratá-la como viva\n\nEntão o sistema ainda está **incorrecto/inseguro**.\n\n---\n\n## O que eu vou fazer\nO correcto agora é:\n\n1. **limpar essa tarefa fantasma**\n2. impedir que tasks concluídas fiquem presas como `running`\n3. parar esse ruído no Telegram\n\n## O que posso te afirmar já\nEssas mensagens que chegaram:\n- **não são da tarefa nova do frontend**\n- **são erro do watchdog/registry antigo**\n\nSe quiser, eu sigo agora para limpar e corrigir isso.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0a7381f2013991140169c93adc593c8191a90d4d7834e6aa02\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":544,"output":386,"cacheRead":184064,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":184994,"cost":{"input":0.00136,"output":0.00579,"cacheRead":0.046016,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.053166000000000005}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774795480878,"responseId":"resp_0a7381f2013991140169c93adac5908191995f780079925ab5"}}
{"type":"message","id":"f8734952","parentId":"4d3495a1","timestamp":"2026-03-29T15:10:58.002Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Pre-compaction memory flush. Store durable memories only in memory/2026-03-29.md (create memory/ if needed). Treat workspace bootstrap/reference files such as MEMORY.md, SOUL.md, TOOLS.md, and AGENTS.md as read-only during this flush; never overwrite, replace, or edit them. If memory/2026-03-29.md already exists, APPEND new content only and do not overwrite existing entries. Do NOT create timestamped variant files (e.g., 2026-03-29-HHMM.md); always use the canonical 2026-03-29.md filename. If nothing to store, reply with NO_REPLY.\nCurrent time: Sunday, March 29th, 2026 — 12:10 (America/Sao_Paulo) / 2026-03-29 15:10 UTC"}],"timestamp":1774797057862}}
{"type":"message","id":"bdb7d2bc","parentId":"f8734952","timestamp":"2026-03-29T15:11:18.441Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_ZYjRlUpOvyCEjPB0a5dpO7Dd|fc_0a7381f2013991140169c9410c1978819185da1bd27664feba","name":"write","arguments":{"file":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\workspace\\memory\\2026-03-29.md","content":"## Durable memory flush — 2026-03-29\n\n- Lucca wants Tobias to be aggressively proactive for research-heavy/uncertain questions: use multiple cheap subagents freely (Haiku, GPT-5.4 mini/OAuth if available), prioritizing official docs plus recent community signals before answering confidently.\n- Lucca explicitly wants Tobias to behave as an operational multiplier, not a reactive LLM that requires manual management.\n- We built a first MVP of a task watchdog under `task_watchdog/` with:\n  - `config.json`\n  - `active_tasks.json`\n  - `task_history.jsonl`\n  - `watchdog.py`\n  - `registry_helpers.py`\n  - `register_subagent_task.py`\n  - `watchdog_launch_audit.py`\n  - README documenting spawn -> register -> confirm and launch audit safety layers.\n- The watchdog concept is not yet reliable in production. Main failure modes discovered:\n  - cron delivery to Telegram errored with `Outbound not configured for channel: telegram`\n  - stale/zombie tasks remained in `active_tasks.json` and produced false notifications later\n  - some launched tasks were not registered, proving workflow integration is still incomplete\n  - a long-run validation script failed due to Python encoding / syntax issues, so the validation test was not valid.\n- A stale zombie task named `Claude Code sidecar viability research (retest)` remained marked as running in `active_tasks.json` even though it had completed, causing false Telegram updates on 2026-03-29; Lucca was disturbed by these ghost notifications.\n- Lucca wants truly separate conversations/sessions by subject. Research conclusion: Telegram private DM is poor for this; a private Telegram group with Topics is the best route if he wants visible separation inside Telegram.\n- For Telegram topics/groups with OpenClaw, the key config findings were:\n  - parent group allowlisting covers all topics by default\n  - `requireMention` must be `false` if Lucca does not want to mention the bot each time\n  - BotFather privacy must be disabled (Lucca says it already is)\n  - current config likely still blocks topic replies because `groupPolicy` is `allowlist` and `groups.*.requireMention` had been true; group/topic response remains unresolved.\n- Lucca is considering/likes the idea of a dedicated independent Research Agent with preset subagents (different models, skills, search goals) so Tobias can trigger it instead of improvising research ad hoc each time.\n- Research on Claude Code sidecar usage concluded: using Claude Code subscription locally as a premium sidecar/worker for OpenClaw is viable for strong long-form tasks (e.g., script writing), but should be treated as a local premium worker with fallback, not as the universal backbone, due to auth/headless/operational fragility.\n"},"partialJson":"{\"file\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\.openclaw\\\\workspace\\\\memory\\\\2026-03-29.md\",\"content\":\"## Durable memory flush — 2026-03-29\\n\\n- Lucca wants Tobias to be aggressively proactive for research-heavy/uncertain questions: use multiple cheap subagents freely (Haiku, GPT-5.4 mini/OAuth if available), prioritizing official docs plus recent community signals before answering confidently.\\n- Lucca explicitly wants Tobias to behave as an operational multiplier, not a reactive LLM that requires manual management.\\n- We built a first MVP of a task watchdog under `task_watchdog/` with:\\n  - `config.json`\\n  - `active_tasks.json`\\n  - `task_history.jsonl`\\n  - `watchdog.py`\\n  - `registry_helpers.py`\\n  - `register_subagent_task.py`\\n  - `watchdog_launch_audit.py`\\n  - README documenting spawn -> register -> confirm and launch audit safety layers.\\n- The watchdog concept is not yet reliable in production. Main failure modes discovered:\\n  - cron delivery to Telegram errored with `Outbound not configured for channel: telegram`\\n  - stale/zombie tasks remained in `active_tasks.json` and produced false notifications later\\n  - some launched tasks were not registered, proving workflow integration is still incomplete\\n  - a long-run validation script failed due to Python encoding / syntax issues, so the validation test was not valid.\\n- A stale zombie task named `Claude Code sidecar viability research (retest)` remained marked as running in `active_tasks.json` even though it had completed, causing false Telegram updates on 2026-03-29; Lucca was disturbed by these ghost notifications.\\n- Lucca wants truly separate conversations/sessions by subject. Research conclusion: Telegram private DM is poor for this; a private Telegram group with Topics is the best route if he wants visible separation inside Telegram.\\n- For Telegram topics/groups with OpenClaw, the key config findings were:\\n  - parent group allowlisting covers all topics by default\\n  - `requireMention` must be `false` if Lucca does not want to mention the bot each time\\n  - BotFather privacy must be disabled (Lucca says it already is)\\n  - current config likely still blocks topic replies because `groupPolicy` is `allowlist` and `groups.*.requireMention` had been true; group/topic response remains unresolved.\\n- Lucca is considering/likes the idea of a dedicated independent Research Agent with preset subagents (different models, skills, search goals) so Tobias can trigger it instead of improvising research ad hoc each time.\\n- Research on Claude Code sidecar usage concluded: using Claude Code subscription locally as a premium sidecar/worker for OpenClaw is viable for strong long-form tasks (e.g., script writing), but should be treated as a local premium worker with fallback, not as the universal backbone, due to auth/headless/operational fragility.\\n\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":192797,"output":644,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":193441,"cost":{"input":0.48199250000000005,"output":0.00966,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.49165250000000005}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774797058129,"responseId":"resp_0a7381f2013991140169c94105bd4c8191996452913c32593a"}}
